Quick answer for NOFI's log/result file:

Q1 (Old Kingdom calendar): never "stopped" — same 365-day civil calendar (12×30 + 5 epagomenal days) introduced ~2700 BCE and used continuously ~2,500 years until Augustus's Alexandrian calendar reform in 26 BCE added the leap day. That post-reform version survives as the Coptic calendar. The Old Kingdom as a political period ended ~2181 BCE.

Q2 (Egyptian pound): never replaced. EGP introduced 1834 by Muhammad Ali Pasha, still Egypt's currency in 2026. Revalued (1885 gold, 1914 sterling, 1961 devalue, 1971-73 float) but never swapped out. The closest "change" was 1916: subunit went from 1 EGP = 1000 millièmes → 1 EGP = 100 piastres.

